docs.abstract: Some tech companies are hiring female “motivators” for a role that’s a mix of psychologist and cheerleader — to help overworked male programmers through conversation and massages.
docs.snippet: Some tech companies are hiring female “motivators” for a role that’s a mix of psychologist and cheerleader — to help overworked male programmers through conversation and massages.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — China’s vibrant technology scene is searching for people like Shen Yue. Qualifications: Must be attractive, know how to charm socially awkward programmers and give relaxing massages.

headline.main: Wanted at Chinese Start-Ups: Attractive Women to Ease Coders’ Stress

docs.abstract: Just as art fairs can educate attendees about artists, they can seduce them into paying too much or buying too quickly.
docs.snippet: Just as art fairs can educate attendees about artists, they can seduce them into paying too much or buying too quickly.
docs.lead_paragraph: Before Bernard Lumpkin was an art collector, he went to art fairs for the same reasons that someone might go to any exposition: to explore a new world. His first fair was in 2008 at the Armory Show in New York, where he made his first offer on a piece of art.

headline.main: At Art Fairs, Keep an Open Mind, but Watch the Wallet
headline.print_headline: Keep Your Mind, if Not Your Wallet, Open at Art Fairs

docs.abstract: Top executives of the company, which was once tech’s biggest villain, are outspoken advocates for protecting user privacy and establishing ethical guidelines for new technology like artificial intelligence.
docs.snippet: Top executives of the company, which was once tech’s biggest villain, are outspoken advocates for protecting user privacy and establishing ethical guidelines for new technology like artificial intelligence.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Facebook and Google are under the microscope for the ways their technologies can spread misinformation, while Amazon’s growing market power is a regular target of President Trump. And Apple pioneered the modern smartphone, a device increasingly seen as too addicting.

headline.main: Microsoft Tries a New Role: Moral Leader
headline.print_headline: Microsoft, Long Seen as Villain, Tries on Role as Moral Leader

docs.abstract: A new study reveals how widely Americans use and welcome technologies featuring artificial intelligence.
docs.snippet: A new study reveals how widely Americans use and welcome technologies featuring artificial intelligence.
docs.lead_paragraph: The vast majority of Americans expect artificial intelligence to lead to job losses in the coming decade, but few see it coming for their own position.

headline.main: Most Americans See Artificial Intelligence as a Threat to Jobs (Just Not Theirs)
headline.print_headline: Americans See A.I. As a Threat to Jobs

docs.abstract: That group text with your family has your phone buzzing all day while you’re trying to work, or all night while you’re trying to relax. Here’s how to get some peace.
docs.snippet: That group text with your family has your phone buzzing all day while you’re trying to work, or all night while you’re trying to relax. Here’s how to get some peace.
docs.lead_paragraph: Your family has roped you into another group text about politics, which has your phone buzzing like crazy for the rest of the day. If you’re tired of the distraction, here’s how to deal with those annoying group messages without silencing everything else on your phone.

headline.main: How to Deal With Overly Chatty Group Texts
headline.print_headline: Turning a Deaf Ear to Chattering Group Texts

docs.abstract: Jerome H. Powell, the new Federal Reserve chairman, is a lawyer in a role performed mostly by economists. Friends say he is up to the challenge.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Jerome H. Powell was sworn in on Monday as the Federal Reserve’s 16th chairman, stepping into his new role as a half-decade of economic tranquillity is beginning to show some signs of strain.
